  "body": "Easiest way to reproduce this is to initialize a hardhat project and run this script with `hh run`:\r\n\r\n```js\r\nasync function main() {\r\n  console.log(Date.now());\r\n\r\n  const blockTimestamp = (await network.provider.send(\"eth_getBlockByNumber\", [\"0x0\", false])).timestamp\r\n\r\n  console.log(parseInt(blockTimestamp.slice(2), 16));\r\n}\r\n\r\nmain()\r\n  .then(() => process.exit(0))\r\n  .catch(error => {\r\n    console.error(error);\r\n    process.exit(1);\r\n  });\r\n```\r\n\r\nSome example results of running this:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ hh run script.js\r\n1617980772445\r\n1617980773\r\n\r\n$ hh run script.js\r\n1617980775866\r\n1617980777\r\n\r\n$ hh run script.js\r\n1617980778351\r\n1617980779\r\n```\r\n\r\nNotice that the first line is the result of `Date.now()`, which is before the timestamp of the genesis block.\r\n\r\n@iamdefinitelyahuman suggested that this could be a rounding thing since block timestamps are in seconds.",
